The PL of PCQDs showed an excitation-dependent nature (Fig. 2
                     ), which was identical to the previous reports [5–13,15]. And the intensity of the PL was varied with the change of excitation wavelengths. Accordingly, there was an optimal excitation wavelength for the brightest PL of PCQDs. Moreover, the optimal excitation wavelength of PCQDs was concentration-dependent, too. Fig. 3
                     A showed the absorption spectra of PCQDs solution with different concentrations. It was found, with the decrease of the concentration of PCQDs, their absorption intensity at near ultraviolet region reduced gradually. The comparative concentration of PCQDs was utilized as an abscissa to investigate the correlation between the optimal emission/excitation wavelength and their concentrations. The results were listed in Fig. 3B. Obviously, the optimal emission/excitation wavelength red shifted with increasing the concentration of PCQDs, possibly due to the fluorescence-resonance energy transfer between PCQDs with different sizes [18].
